value.value: The presence of multiple meningiomas in the leptomeninges.
A benign or malignant, gonadal or extragonadal neoplasm that originates from germ cells. Representative examples include teratoma, seminoma, embryonal carcinoma, and yolk sac tumor.
A population of antibody-secreting cells in the blood that are highly proliferative and may act as precursors for plasma cells.
A benign, borderline, or malignant neoplasm that arises from and is composed of epithelial cells. Representative examples include adenomas and carcinomas.

A glycosidic antineoplastic antibiotic isolated from the bacterium Streptomyces griseus.  Chromomycin antibiotics bind to the minor groove of DNA, specifically to guanine/cytosine base pairs, and inhibit RNA synthesis.
A rare benign neoplasm arising from tooth-forming tissues. It is characterized by the presence of a fibromyxoid stroma, epithelial component, dentin, and enamel. Recurrences are rare.

Neoplastic Round Cell with Lipomatous Differentiation

value.value: A benign or malignant cell that is characterized by the presence of a small nucleus and scant amount of cytoplasm.  It may be epithelial, lymphoid, neuroepithelial, or mesenchymal in origin.

Neoplastic Large Cell with Abundant Cytoplasm

value.value: A benign, slow growing, and painless hamartomatous tumor occurring in tooth-bearing areas of the jaws. It usually affects children and adolescents. It is characterized by the presence of tooth-like structures. Treatment consists of local excision. Recurrences have not been reported.
